WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960
Thank you.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:02.440
Thank you.

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:02.760
Hello.

00:00:02.760 --> 00:00:08.220
This will be at protocol related, just so you know.

00:00:08.220 --> 00:00:11.270
The description does not make it sound that way, but I

00:00:11.270 --> 00:00:12.210
promise it will.

00:00:12.220 --> 00:00:14.460
For one thing, there's a leaflet link.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:18.320
As Boris said, I have been writing about this for a

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:19.120
while.

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:23.030
I've also been thinking about this topic and speaking and writing

00:00:23.030 --> 00:00:27.750
and practicing things around this for almost 20 years.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:32.570
That sounds probably pretty crazy because we haven't had generative

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:35.050
software that long, but I'm going to talk to you

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:37.310
about architectural patterns today.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:41.240
I want to set it up and tell you about what I

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:42.960
was thinking.

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:45.960
Probably a lot of us started thinking about Vibe Coding

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:48.720
, before it was called Vibe Coding, three more

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:49.430
years ago.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:52.760
The first thought I thought, you know, back in 2023

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:56.980
was like, you know, someday people will actually like allow

00:00:56.980 --> 00:00:59.290
agents to write code and they won't even review the code

00:00:59.290 --> 00:00:59.440
.

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:00.670
That sounded crazy, you know.

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:02.840
And then it's like, oh, next year, okay

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:05.080
, a lot of people are going to do this.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:07.020
And now I'm thinking, of course, everyone's going

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:07.500
to do it.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:08.960
Why is everyone going to do it?

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:10.380
Because people are lazy.

00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:12.160
Right?

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:12.990
They are.

00:01:12.990 --> 00:01:14.150
They are lazy.

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:15.760
Agents are not lazy.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:18.400
And all of us with the best intentions, when we are

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:21.200
stressed, we will do the easiest possible thing.

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:25.350
So I started thinking about if we know they're going to

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:27.400
do it, how can we make it okay?

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:29.140
And I should say it this way so it doesn't sound

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:30.380
like I'm judging anyone.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.140
If I know I'm going to do it, how can

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:32.930
we make it okay?

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:35.390
And not just for trivial Vibe Coded one shot apps

00:01:35.390 --> 00:01:35.570
.

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:36.520
That's a demo.

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:37.400
That's a magic trick.

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:38.860
That doesn't matter in real life.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:41.790
It's fun, but it doesn't matter.

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:44.820
So the thing that occurred to me is, and I was

00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:48.520
talking to a bunch of nerd friends, you know, old

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:52.250
people like me, about if I'm looking at something like

00:01:52.250 --> 00:01:54.640
a pure function written in Haskell.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:01:55.920
This isn't Haskell because I didn't want you to

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:57.950
have to try to read that.

00:01:57.960 --> 00:01:59.720
Pure function written in Haskell.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:01.840
So no side effects, great type system.

00:02:01.840 --> 00:02:04.430
The language can ensure there are no side effects.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:06.880
You know what the input and the output types are.

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:08.640
The names are great, et cetera.

00:02:08.650 --> 00:02:12.840
I pretty much thought even three years ago, I can tell

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.040
ChatGPT in the little ChatGPT program

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:15.820
to create that.

00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:17.990
I can just copy and paste it in, probably trust it

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:19.490
, never have to verify it.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:23.650
We've all sort of had that intuition that small focused things

00:02:23.730 --> 00:02:26.200
are probably okay, and it's probably going to do a

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:27.190
good job, right?

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:29.810
And so I started thinking about this like, well, what

00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:32.430
's the difference between that and a whole system?

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:35.370
And really the whole system, it's about shapes.

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:38.230
So I just described a bunch of things that were about shapes

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.650
, it was about size, it was about like the boundaries

00:02:40.810 --> 00:02:42.760
of the function, the type system, the names, all

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:43.520
these things.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:47.360
It's easy to replace something that is that small.

00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.920
It's also easy to generate something correct that small.

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:52.680
So this led me on a whole adventure, but I'm

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:55.430
going to go back in time a little bit to 2014.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:57.940
Did any of you live through Heartbleed?

00:02:57.940 --> 00:02:59.060
Yeah.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:02.910
So if you were working at a company that had any production

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:05.800
systems when Heartbleed happened, I was at Wunder

00:03:05.800 --> 00:03:07.760
list in Berlin at the time I was CTO.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:11.370
I woke up one morning and my colleague, James Duncan Davidson

00:03:11.370 --> 00:03:14.180
, who was the creator of Tomcat and Ant, another

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:16.960
old school guy, had sent me a message saying, we

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:19.020
have to turn off the entire service.

00:03:19.030 --> 00:03:20.630
That's how I woke up that morning.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:22.360
I was like, oh my God, what did we do

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:22.660
wrong?

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:24.960
We didn't do anything wrong.

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:27.690
So Heartbleed was a bug in OpenSSL that

00:03:27.690 --> 00:03:32.400
it was just a mistake that allowed leakage of private data just

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:36.310
to anyone on the internet that could access the service.

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:37.900
And it was a disaster.

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:39.180
It was such a disaster.

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:42.190
So we had a microservices architecture and we've been doing

00:03:42.190 --> 00:03:45.720
something called immutable infrastructure long before that was a thing that

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:46.410
everyone did.

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:49.650
It was before Docker was like in major circulation and usage.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:51.260
It was still pretty early.

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:55.310
And so we had hundreds of services, which means we had

00:03:55.730 --> 00:03:59.060
hundreds of computers that had a bad version of OpenSSL

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:03.110
that were running in production with millions of active users.

00:04:03.110 --> 00:04:04.170
So what did we do?

00:04:04.170 --> 00:04:06.360
I mean, that's a panic situation.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:09.150
I remember looking at the Amazon, AWS dashboard at all the

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:11.470
things and just thinking, what are we going to do?

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:12.790
We were waiting for Amazon.

00:04:12.790 --> 00:04:14.050
They were not responding.

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:16.510
They were very busy, as you might guess, that day

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:16.780
.

00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:19.420
And so we said, well, as soon as we have

00:04:19.420 --> 00:04:21.740
a good OpenSSL image, we're just going to

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:26.570
replace literally every server, hundreds of servers, 300-ish

00:04:26.570 --> 00:04:28.320
instances at the time.

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:29.980
How did we do it?

00:04:29.980 --> 00:04:31.400
I went to a computer.

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:32.360
I was afraid.

00:04:32.360 --> 00:04:33.630
I typed a command.

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:36.450
And over the course of a couple of hours, they all

00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:37.100
got replaced.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:38.250
Nothing ever went down.

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:39.200
And it just worked.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.520
Why?

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:45.960
Because the system was built to be a massive system of small

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:47.600
components.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:51.920
And it was always built with the idea that these components would

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:52.680
be destroyed.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:55.140
That's the idea behind immutable infrastructure.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:56.650
You never change a server.

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:57.600
You only modify it.

00:04:57.650 --> 00:04:59.860
Or the only way you modify a server is by replacing it

00:04:59.860 --> 00:04:59.990
.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:02.180
So if you need to upgrade something, you throw away the

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:03.930
old thing, you replace it with a new thing.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.130
Kind of old hat infrastructure now.

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:07.550
If you're a DevOps-y kind of person, that

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:08.720
's how you do it, probably.

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:10.430
If not, apologies to you.

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:11.540
You should get a new job.

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:13.690
So it took us a day.

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:17.220
It took most teams weeks or a week.

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:20.440
There are still 250,000-ish servers on the internet

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:24.090
that are suffering from this problem, which means 250,000

00:05:24.090 --> 00:05:27.340
compromised servers that you can get private data out of for whatever

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:27.800
reason.

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:30.610
But this problem is sort of solved, right?

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:32.110
This is more than 10 years ago.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:34.140
Here's an imaginary scenario.

00:05:34.180 --> 00:05:38.220
Later on this year, the Lazarus group in North Korea

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:43.140
infects some packages in NPM, or whatever package manager

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:43.230
.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:47.120
And the infection goes like a virus through the network, and

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:49.980
it starts infecting all the other packages.

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:52.530
And at the end of the day, you wake up to

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:57.060
the news that the entire JavaScript ecosystem is compromised.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:58.840
What do you do?

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:02.040
You can't delete all the servers and restart them because N

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:03.290
PM itself is compromised.

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:04.640
Everything is compromised.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.030
You can't trust anything in the ecosystem.

00:06:07.030 --> 00:06:09.980
You have to actually move to a new language and a new

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:10.810
ecosystem.

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:13.460
So let's do that in a day, yeah?

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:15.540
On a complicated application.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:17.040
Probably not, right?

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:18.520
But that's the idea.

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:22.040
You would need to delete everything and regenerate it.

00:06:22.070 --> 00:06:24.490
It would be an absolute disaster.

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:29.210
So this is the goal of the architecture that I'm putting

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:30.300
forward here.

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:33.580
And you probably can't read it because it's too small

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:33.690
.

00:06:33.740 --> 00:06:36.850
These are command lines that say like Phoenix generate and regenerate

00:06:36.850 --> 00:06:39.650
, and the idea is just like replace all the implementations

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:41.030
of everything that we have.

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:43.040
Say like from NPM, we're going to go ahead

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:46.780
and finally move to Rust like everybody else.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:48.670
So one last story.

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:52.380
Early in my career, this is over 20 years ago,

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:55.390
I was going, I was like moving up the career ladder

00:06:55.390 --> 00:06:55.570
.

00:06:55.620 --> 00:06:57.140
I was at a big public company.

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:59.600
I was moving toward a CIO position in one of the

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:02.320
sub, you know, the divisions of the company.

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:05.050
And I was asked to do a new job.

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:08.600
The new job was pretty surprising given my career path.

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:12.540
It was to be the lone developer developer that took over another

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:15.490
system from a guy who was trolling the company.

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:19.150
So this guy had written this really complex system in C that

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:22.820
was talking to the Moby Tech's radio frequency network.

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:26.420
It was managing laptops in the field for service technicians.

00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:29.440
It was basically like a bespoke message queuing system.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:30.940
Like you'd do RabbitMQ today.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:32.570
He had built his own thing then.

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:35.460
No one knew how this thing worked.

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:35.880
Why?

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:39.420
Because the only real artifact of the system was the code.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:42.800
It was a bunch of conversations that had happened in ugly conference

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:44.790
rooms in this company over the years.

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:46.390
It was all in production.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:49.080
This guy was the only person who knew how any of it

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:49.670
worked.

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:51.400
Really knew how it worked.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:55.550
But he was basically holding us hostage as a company.

00:07:55.630 --> 00:07:59.420
So I went from move towards CIO to go sit up

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:03.030
all night in an office in the dark like doing s-

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:06.820
trace on server processes trying to figure out what this thing

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:07.820
does.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:10.730
So this can happen today and it could happen 20 years ago

00:08:10.730 --> 00:08:10.820
.

00:08:10.930 --> 00:08:13.010
You can be held hostage by your code base.

00:08:13.010 --> 00:08:17.110
So I learned something very early around that time in my career

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:19.980
from a guy named Kent Beck who is the creator of extreme

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:21.820
programming and a bunch of other stuff.

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:24.380
And if you're my age in software development, he's

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:26.690
probably one of your software development heroes.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:29.820
If something hurts, do it more frequently.

00:08:29.820 --> 00:08:32.460
So with extreme programming, which was the precursor to agile

00:08:32.560 --> 00:08:35.490
, which ruined everything and they never should have done the agile

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:35.830
thing.

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:38.830
But extreme programming, it was like merging is hard.

00:08:38.920 --> 00:08:40.340
You need to do continuous integration.

00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:41.050
Deployment is hard.

00:08:41.050 --> 00:08:42.520
You know, we learned all these things.

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:43.540
Testing is hard.

00:08:43.540 --> 00:08:45.780
You should do it up front so no code is written without

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:46.170
a test.

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:47.250
Code review is hard.

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:48.600
Just do pair programming.

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:49.260
Constant, right?

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:53.460
So if updating code is hard and making changes to code is

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:56.240
hard, the Kent Beck version of that would be just do

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:58.780
it constantly, like all day maybe.

00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:00.660
So how do you do that?

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:05.540
That means that the code itself is not that important sort of

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:06.120
, right?

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:07.330
If you're going to be replacing it all the time,

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:09.050
if you're going to be throwing it away and replacing it

00:09:09.050 --> 00:09:10.500
, how do you do it?

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:13.260
And then another person who's not as smart as Kent once

00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:16.250
said the mutability of a system is enhanced by the imm

00:09:16.250 --> 00:09:17.580
utability of its components.

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:20.300
I said that, but you know, I like to quote

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:21.860
myself because I think it's a pretty good one.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:24.500
So maybe in 20 years or so, someone will say,

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:26.540
if it was me, you heard Chad say this and it

00:09:26.540 --> 00:09:27.640
was meaningful to you.

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:32.240
So the weird thing about this is, you know, we

00:09:32.290 --> 00:09:33.620
're in this weird era.

00:09:33.660 --> 00:09:36.950
How many of you are actually software developers, by the way

00:09:36.950 --> 00:09:37.240
?

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:38.000
Okay, good.

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:41.010
Enough of you that that some of you will feel sad about

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.980
this sort of, you know, is the craft going away

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:44.300
?

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:46.470
I've been posting a bunch of stuff on that leaflet

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:47.270
and people get mad.

00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:49.610
Every time I post something, there's at least someone who

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:51.890
is angry and like, you know, you're wrong,

00:09:51.890 --> 00:09:52.350
idiot.

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:54.270
You were influenced by marketing.

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:56.490
That was yesterday's post actually.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:58.670
But the craft doesn't disappear.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:09:59.560
It just moves.

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:02.530
So, you know, from like doing test driven development,

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:05.240
you need to be thinking about how you evaluate the code from

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:09.160
a business perspective and from a like architectural perspective in terms of

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:11.620
what the technical requirements are of the code.

00:10:11.660 --> 00:10:15.010
You know, you'll be thinking about things like what are

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:18.460
the boundaries and what is the actual architecture that can work in

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:21.020
a system that's constantly replacing itself?

00:10:21.030 --> 00:10:22.370
How can that possibly work?

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:24.010
And so I'm going to dig into that kind of stuff

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:24.220
.

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:29.410
One note here, though, is there is still very much

00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:32.890
a craft or an engineering discipline or whatever sort of metaphor you

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:33.630
want to use.

00:10:33.630 --> 00:10:33.880
Art.

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:35.080
You know, I'm a musician.

00:10:35.150 --> 00:10:37.050
So maybe there's a craft or there's an art to

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:37.310
it.

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:41.140
And what I'm seeing now and the fear that a lot

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:46.060
of people have in the software industry is that the senior people

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.510
and senior doesn't have to mean old or even experienced,

00:10:48.600 --> 00:10:52.990
but somehow the people who have gained wisdom in this field somehow

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:58.780
, they are moving farther and farther away from the newbies

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:04.480
because everything moves so quickly and the mistakes you make have such

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:08.740
great and instant ramifications and the good choices you make have

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:13.690
such major ramifications that this AI thing amplifies the effect

00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:15.340
of this experience.

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:20.140
So Phoenix Architecture, what is it?

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:24.290
It's a name that I let the AI choose, honestly

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:24.540
.

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:27.280
This is the thing I do because naming is one of the

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:28.580
hardest things, right?

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:29.900
So that's why we have LLMs.

00:11:29.900 --> 00:11:31.780
You never have to name anything again.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:34.180
Just make sure it's not offensive in any language if you

00:11:34.190 --> 00:11:36.080
can, but you can ask the LLM that too

00:11:36.130 --> 00:11:36.330
.

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:40.380
It's an architectural idea, a bunch of architectural principles.

00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:45.260
As I said, they are extracted from my decades of thinking

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:48.380
about this problem and trying to figure out how we can create

00:11:48.620 --> 00:11:50.460
systems that can survive.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:53.820
So if you Google for me, if anyone uses Google anymore

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.580
and put the word legacy, you will find me talking about

00:11:56.610 --> 00:11:57.680
this back in 2009.

00:11:57.680 --> 00:11:59.360
And some of the things I'm going to say are the

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:02.990
same today because I realized that making systems that can survive,

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:05.860
the principles have been the same for a long time.

00:12:05.910 --> 00:12:10.290
It's also a reference implementation of this architecture.

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:12.710
And I'm going to show you two things very briefly on

00:12:12.710 --> 00:12:16.330
the reference implementation and you can find it on Tangled or

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:18.690
you can find it on the copy on GitHub, but obviously

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:20.620
you're all going to use Tangled, right?

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:26.610
So I'm starting to think about software not as a thing

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:29.170
where you go into an editor, you know, that's

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:32.760
always been like a short version of what the AI thing would

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:34.650
be, these co-pilot things in an IDE that

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:38.510
's gone already, but rather a pipeline.

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:43.490
So we go from specifications to something else, to something else

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:46.080
, to something else that ends up generating code.

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:47.930
And the something else is here.

00:12:47.970 --> 00:12:49.840
You won't be able to read this, but you can

00:12:49.890 --> 00:12:51.270
just kind of see columns here.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.820
Imagine you've got a bunch of markdown specifications.

00:12:53.820 --> 00:12:56.170
Those are just things where you just type stuff.

00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:59.290
Maybe you're also in a chat program like Freq.

00:12:59.300 --> 00:13:01.460
Ask me about Freq, F-R-E-

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:02.110
E-Q.

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:05.900
From that will be extracted clauses.

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:08.380
So you can use LLMs for this.

00:13:08.380 --> 00:13:10.490
It's not quite, you know, perfect, but my

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:12.750
reference implementation does some hacks.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:15.700
You extract clauses, which are like different ways of saying the

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:16.300
same thing.

00:13:16.300 --> 00:13:18.630
You can kind of deduplicate them into those text

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:19.300
chunks.

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:22.720
From that, you can canonicalize and deduplicate

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:24.620
actual requirements.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:27.360
From that, you can expand them into various things that you

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:28.290
want to evaluate.

00:13:28.290 --> 00:13:29.610
They could be invariants.

00:13:29.710 --> 00:13:32.050
They could be various other constraints.

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:35.820
They might even be things like this component must be fast,

00:13:35.820 --> 00:13:39.260
which turns into this component must respond within 50 milliseconds.

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:40.620
So that becomes a constraint.

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:43.990
And from there, you go into the implementation, which I

00:13:44.020 --> 00:13:46.590
'm going to talk about in a second, has two phases

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:48.210
, sort of, necessarily.

00:13:48.210 --> 00:13:55.250
The cool thing about this is if you create a system like

00:13:55.290 --> 00:13:57.890
this, where you're actually thinking of that end piece,

00:13:57.900 --> 00:13:59.820
the code, as a compiled artifact.

00:13:59.820 --> 00:14:01.930
Think of it as a binary, like TypeScript or whatever

00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:02.820
you're generating.

00:14:02.820 --> 00:14:03.770
It's like binary code.

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:04.780
You wouldn't edit it.

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:09.140
It also means that you can trace the provenance from the

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:11.800
markdown file, from a piece of text in the mark

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:14.600
down file, through this graph of requirements, all the way

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:16.800
through to the generated thing at the end.

00:14:16.800 --> 00:14:19.280
So just like you were doing a C program or something,

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:21.940
where you're compiling from C to an object file to

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:24.670
blah, blah, blah, the TypeScript is just in

00:14:24.670 --> 00:14:26.070
that dependent path.

00:14:26.130 --> 00:14:28.940
And so when you set up a system like this, you

00:14:28.970 --> 00:14:30.020
can do two things.

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:32.610
One is you can regenerate just the path down to the

00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:35.310
component at the end that you want to generate.

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:38.210
The other is, if someone does do the wrong thing,

00:14:38.210 --> 00:14:41.500
so I say, and edit the code themselves as a human

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:43.420
, you can see where it drifts.

00:14:43.430 --> 00:14:45.540
And you can see, well, the drift is here,

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:47.170
and it actually affects this spec.

00:14:47.180 --> 00:14:50.630
And I could even, like, automatically analyze the code and

00:14:50.710 --> 00:14:53.970
see it's changed the spec in a certain way.

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:55.180
Is that actually the spec now?

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:56.290
Is that what you meant?

00:14:56.330 --> 00:14:58.590
And commit it as the real intent of the code.

00:14:58.630 --> 00:15:01.620
Because intent is what matters more than anything else now.

00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:03.180
Intent plus architecture.

00:15:03.180 --> 00:15:07.020
Let me put this back in full screen.

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:07.850
Or not.

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:13.340
This is the fun of creating your own presentation software.

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:19.370
So when I was implementing this, I realized when I got

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:21.500
to a certain point, you know, I'm going to

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:22.780
generate some code.

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:24.920
What the hell am I going to generate?

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:27.020
Like, is it a React application?

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:28.060
Is it a Next.

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:29.200
js application?

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:30.390
Is it a Rust thing?

00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:32.300
The answer is, I don't know.

00:15:32.300 --> 00:15:34.880
And not only do I not know, I don't want

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:38.560
to have to, for a given application, decide those things

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:38.860
.

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:41.770
Because I want to be able to move from, let's

00:15:41.770 --> 00:15:45.550
say, JavaScript to Rust when the Lazarus group takes over

00:15:45.550 --> 00:15:46.140
NPM.

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:48.610
They're not going to, but if they did, I

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:50.130
want that flexibility.

00:15:50.140 --> 00:15:52.660
And the real-life story behind that is, at W

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:54.970
underlist, again, we launched Wunderlist 3,

00:15:54.970 --> 00:15:58.040
which was our huge rewrite that finally made the sync work and

00:15:58.060 --> 00:15:59.920
everyone was happy with it.

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:03.030
We launched it with Ruby on Rails as the backend.

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:08.030
Lovely for humans, not great for compute, very expensive to

00:16:08.030 --> 00:16:08.500
run.

00:16:08.660 --> 00:16:12.300
But the way we had architected this back in 2013-

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:15.290
14, allowed us, for the same reasons that we could

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:18.780
fix the Heartbleed problem, allowed us to rewrite each

00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:22.220
service in another language within three months.

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:26.640
And we went from, I'll just say we saved 70

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:30.730
% of our compute costs by rewriting services without affecting the

00:16:30.730 --> 00:16:31.390
system.

00:16:31.390 --> 00:16:34.120
Because we were just replacing the components.

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:36.510
So in a system like this, if we're building this

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:40.120
for agents, if we're building this for a constantly regener

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:44.100
ating world, we need to compile not to an implementation,

00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:47.710
but we need to compile to an architecture that has these properties

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:51.140
of components with boundaries that are just like that Haskell thing

00:16:51.170 --> 00:16:54.380
I was talking about earlier that can be replaced at will because

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:55.930
the boundaries are clear enough.

00:16:55.980 --> 00:17:00.780
So the idea is you have some intent.

00:17:00.780 --> 00:17:02.440
Maybe it comes from a conversation.

00:17:02.480 --> 00:17:04.100
Usually they come from conversation.

00:17:04.100 --> 00:17:06.060
Maybe documents, lots of conversations.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:11.230
The intent is then compiled into some decisions, not into code

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:12.220
necessarily.

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:14.460
The decisions then generate code.

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:17.670
And then they go through an evaluation loop where you see,

00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:19.920
well, is this code actually doing the thing that it's

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:22.580
required to do based on the specs, including all those invari

00:17:22.590 --> 00:17:25.020
ants and constraints and stuff I was talking about earlier.

00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:28.630
That could even be stuff that's coming from observability systems

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:28.800
.

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:33.430
So I think software development in the near future is a closed

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:36.780
loop from production, where you're actually pulling in what's

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:38.060
happening in production.

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:40.820
It's informing and saying, well, this thing has now

00:17:40.820 --> 00:17:42.300
drifted from the requirements.

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:45.420
I think we should regenerate these two components because they're

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:47.900
not doing the thing that the business says they need to do

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:48.060
.

00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:48.690
Right?

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:52.620
So then you record the provenance, which means the chain

00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:56.540
of the human or the human and human's agents, and

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:00.040
all of the different specs and everything else that led to the

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:03.600
generation, capture it forever cryptographically.

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:05.900
Then you deploy it within the boundaries.

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:07.660
Same way I talked about with Wunderlist.

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:11.100
So you're deploying these nice, tight, controlled components.

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:14.070
And then, I won't talk about this now, but

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:17.470
if you read the blog, you will compact because we are

00:18:18.020 --> 00:18:19.710
creating tons and tons of garbage.

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:22.020
Those of us who are making stuff with LLMs now

00:18:22.020 --> 00:18:26.270
, I accidentally created two web interfaces for my IRC network

00:18:26.270 --> 00:18:26.420
.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:28.640
And it took me a while to delete them because I couldn

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:30.530
't remember which one was the right one.

00:18:30.530 --> 00:18:31.420
So there you go.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:37.470
So I should mention what is an evaluation because this is an

00:18:37.490 --> 00:18:38.570
overloaded term now.

00:18:38.570 --> 00:18:39.700
I kind of got into it.

00:18:39.700 --> 00:18:42.130
It's all of these different things, you know, the

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:45.160
requirements that could be just like, it must act like this

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:47.450
, you know, what we're used to with specs and

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:48.390
user stories.

00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:50.800
But it's also, it shouldn't use this much memory

00:18:50.810 --> 00:18:52.340
or it has to be this fast or it has to be

00:18:52.340 --> 00:18:55.700
, you know, deployable on this thing or whatever.

00:18:55.700 --> 00:18:59.490
So evaluations are the thing that are about the system and not

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:00.620
about the code.

00:19:00.620 --> 00:19:03.410
It's not unit tests because unit tests are tied to actual

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:04.400
implementation.

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:06.520
So that's not the thing that you want to rely on

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:06.700
.

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:09.650
That's also a thing that they can generate better than we

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:11.050
can and we should let them.

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:13.690
So it might be, has to have 100% test coverage

00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:16.580
and they always have to pass, that sort of stuff.

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:18.780
That could be one.

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:20.870
And then here's the sort of secret.

00:19:21.140 --> 00:19:25.010
In the flow I showed you earlier where you have specs going

00:19:25.010 --> 00:19:28.940
to canonical requirements, et cetera, et cetera, there are

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:32.570
two things in the, there are two like columns and implementation

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:32.880
.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:36.480
Before you get to the actual implementation, I'm calling this

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:41.360
implementation units because this is actually the decisions about what components should

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:45.220
exist and what their behaviors and boundaries and interfaces need to be

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:45.260
.

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:49.780
This should not be language or runtime dependent.

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:54.260
This is the promise of a thing that will be implemented in

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:58.880
some language and deployed in some runtime that meets the requirements of

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:00.330
the specifications.

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:03.800
And this is a really powerful thing because it means you can

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:06.110
do things like say, well, let's just do a

00:20:06.110 --> 00:20:09.140
pass this afternoon and see if we can make this thing 50

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:09.750
% faster.

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:11.290
Okay, good Friday, deploy it.

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:13.240
You know, that's where we want to get with this

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:13.660
stuff.

00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:17.160
So implementation units are sort of like the semi abstract version of

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:19.660
the thing that you want to test and they're what the

00:20:19.660 --> 00:20:21.070
actual evaluations tie to.

00:20:21.070 --> 00:20:23.630
And the implementations can have unit tests and all the other

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:24.820
stuff that you're used to in your language.

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:28.620
But we are actually past a point now of, I think

00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:30.460
, sorry, language advocacy.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:33.100
And I say that as someone who like, you know,

00:20:33.100 --> 00:20:35.780
I was like, I started the Ruby nonprofit and the Rails

00:20:35.860 --> 00:20:38.200
Conf and RubyConf and wrote the RubyGems thing and

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:40.330
spoke at Ruby conferences and wrote books about Ruby.

00:20:40.350 --> 00:20:42.410
And I was all Ruby, Ruby, Ruby 20 something years

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:42.780
ago.

00:20:42.780 --> 00:20:46.490
And I'm going to RubyConf to receive an award this

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:49.270
year and tell them you probably ought to not use Ruby anymore

00:20:49.270 --> 00:20:49.360
.

00:20:49.470 --> 00:20:50.380
It's not a good idea.

00:20:50.380 --> 00:20:52.380
Because who's Ruby for?

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:53.660
People.

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:55.180
Ruby is for people.

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:58.620
These programs are for machines.

00:20:58.620 --> 00:21:00.800
And what matters now is that they're fast, correct.

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:03.660
You can generate them with LLMs or whatever the technology

00:21:03.670 --> 00:21:04.290
is going to be.

00:21:04.300 --> 00:21:05.260
They're cheap to run.

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:06.210
That's what matters.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:08.210
It doesn't matter what language it is anymore.

00:21:08.210 --> 00:21:10.480
So let go of that, except for your hobby time.

00:21:10.480 --> 00:21:12.620
Write in your hobby time, fine, fun.

00:21:12.620 --> 00:21:14.790
Otherwise, it's irresponsible.

00:21:14.790 --> 00:21:17.400
And that was a, yeah, just throwing some bombs at

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:17.970
you here.

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:18.980
All right.

00:21:19.010 --> 00:21:21.960
And so, you know, the code doesn't matter anymore

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:22.060
.

00:21:22.060 --> 00:21:23.030
We have to let go of that.

00:21:23.090 --> 00:21:24.020
We have a code fetish.

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:26.790
I've been saying that for decades, literally, to developers

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:27.740
at conferences.

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:28.980
We have a code fetish.

00:21:28.980 --> 00:21:30.530
It's not about the code.

00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:33.580
Now it's about these evaluations, really, and the fact

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:35.140
that things need to exist.

00:21:35.140 --> 00:21:39.620
So, sort of backing up a little bit, think about

00:21:39.620 --> 00:21:42.880
, like, I went through the whole microservices movement,

00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:44.430
if you can call it that, craze, hype,

00:21:44.520 --> 00:21:44.970
whatever.

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:46.460
And I was definitely one of them.

00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:49.740
And I'm friends with Fred George, who created that term

00:21:49.860 --> 00:21:51.810
, and probably regrets it now.

00:21:51.820 --> 00:21:54.460
People hate microservices.

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:56.820
Now, there's been a movement to move back to mon

00:21:56.840 --> 00:21:57.420
oliths.

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.630
That's also really stupid and misguided.

00:21:59.630 --> 00:22:03.020
The reason they hate microservices is, like, imagine you

00:22:03.020 --> 00:22:06.190
spent six months, like, breaking apart this monolith into

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.610
a bunch of microservices, because your manager said, we

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:10.280
're doing microservices now.

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:12.960
And then you finally remove the thing, and you realize,

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:15.320
oh, crap, there are all these dependencies we didn't

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:17.660
really understand that are, like, maybe they're temporal,

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:19.020
or they're data-related, or whatever.

00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:21.980
You didn't accomplish anything by doing this.

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:25.860
Maybe some sort of, like, production runtime improvement of not

00:22:25.860 --> 00:22:28.220
having, you know, services get on each other's CPU

00:22:28.220 --> 00:22:31.980
cycles and slow the whole system down, or whatever.

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:33.180
Not good.

00:22:33.470 --> 00:22:37.540
So, this is sort of a necessary thing to think about

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:37.770
.

00:22:37.770 --> 00:22:39.800
Like, it's not just small, but it's about

00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:41.590
boundaries and replaceability.

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:42.900
That's what matters.

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.400
And I say this as a person who did a talk called

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:48.390
Tiny 10 years ago at a conference, thinking, I think

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:50.360
it's just about making things small, guys, but it

00:22:50.360 --> 00:22:50.840
was not.

00:22:50.860 --> 00:22:55.280
Now what I'm realizing, and this is me also sh

00:22:55.320 --> 00:22:59.490
illing my project, I must admit, but really, it

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:00.940
's about the conversation.

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:02.940
So, you know, I was thinking about, like,

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:04.980
how do you apply all this generative AI stuff?

00:23:04.990 --> 00:23:06.710
It's fine for one-shotting apps, and,

00:23:06.710 --> 00:23:09.200
you know, like, I made this presentation with a --

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:10.860
I don't have a slide deck.

00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:13.100
I just have -- talking to an LLM, having

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:13.970
it generate things.

00:23:13.980 --> 00:23:20.710
What really matters, though, on big systems, is context

00:23:20.710 --> 00:23:20.980
.

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:22.540
Like, how do you get the intent?

00:23:22.550 --> 00:23:24.520
How do you go to a 20-year-old system

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:26.930
and find out what the intent is behind the code?

00:23:27.020 --> 00:23:29.060
You probably do not, actually, right?

00:23:29.060 --> 00:23:30.190
Because no one captures it.

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:31.550
There's just no system for that.

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:32.940
There never has been.

00:23:32.940 --> 00:23:35.520
Except in, like, really, really bureaucratic places,

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:39.280
but then it was malicious compliance, and you're going to

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:40.140
end up crap anyway.

00:23:40.140 --> 00:23:43.920
So, what if we could create an environment where the conversation

00:23:43.920 --> 00:23:48.370
is always captured around how the requirements were created and specified,

00:23:48.380 --> 00:23:51.010
tied to a human in a way that is archived and

00:23:51.010 --> 00:23:55.070
will never be lost when you move from Slack to Teams or

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:55.970
something?

00:23:56.070 --> 00:23:59.410
And every commit and every piece of code is tied to that

00:23:59.420 --> 00:24:01.310
conversation and the people that did it, so you get a

00:24:01.310 --> 00:24:01.900
sense of why.

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:05.420
I think this is the only responsible way to do software development

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:05.900
next year.

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:09.490
And to do that, it means you may not touch code

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:10.620
as a human.

00:24:10.620 --> 00:24:12.610
You can view it, like, you shouldn't even be

00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:13.650
able to -- you can use VI.

00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:14.160
It's okay.

00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:15.580
If you use VI, you can change it, but,

00:24:15.580 --> 00:24:17.380
you know, like, don't use VS code and edit

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:17.930
your code.

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:18.620
It's wrong.

00:24:18.620 --> 00:24:21.360
Because if you as a human do it, you can't

00:24:21.410 --> 00:24:22.770
guarantee all this stuff.

00:24:22.800 --> 00:24:25.660
You won't guarantee being able to capture all this provenance

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:25.660
.

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:28.700
And bots are way better at discipline than we are.

00:24:28.700 --> 00:24:33.260
So, I'm going to go kind of fast now.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:36.750
So, I talk about regenerating code.

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:39.210
And I talk about, like, systems -- like, in

00:24:39.310 --> 00:24:42.720
my perfect world, a system in production maybe doesn't have

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:45.150
any of the same code it had last month.

00:24:45.150 --> 00:24:46.860
And that's always true.

00:24:46.860 --> 00:24:48.230
It's just always rolling.

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:50.540
And probably I will think that's quaint in a year

00:24:50.550 --> 00:24:52.290
and say, really, I meant five minutes.

00:24:52.290 --> 00:24:53.260
Sorry, guys, you know.

00:24:53.260 --> 00:24:56.960
That's sort of insane, though, because just because we

00:24:57.010 --> 00:24:58.650
can change it doesn't mean we should.

00:24:58.650 --> 00:24:59.720
And there are layers.

00:24:59.750 --> 00:25:03.540
So, Stuart Brand has this concept of pace layers, which

00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:06.540
is really just about, like, layers of the ability to

00:25:06.550 --> 00:25:09.250
change and where things need to move more slowly and where they

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:10.220
can move more quickly.

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:13.370
An example of a pace layer that should move slowly is like

00:25:13.370 --> 00:25:15.000
a protocol, you know, HTTP.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.620
Let's not change that daily.

00:25:16.620 --> 00:25:18.030
But also a user interface.

00:25:18.080 --> 00:25:20.940
You can't just have the user interface change constantly because your

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:22.470
users will be confused.

00:25:22.540 --> 00:25:24.180
And I think, you know, Paul might have mentioned that

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:25.340
earlier in their presentation.

00:25:25.340 --> 00:25:29.680
The other thing that we need to worry about is hidden state

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:29.980
.

00:25:29.980 --> 00:25:34.090
And I sort of got to that with the with the del

00:25:34.090 --> 00:25:36.450
etion test idea of, you know, doing this big

00:25:36.450 --> 00:25:37.660
microservices thing.

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:41.410
And then you replace the monolith with the microservices and

00:25:41.620 --> 00:25:42.080
nothing works.

00:25:42.130 --> 00:25:45.100
There's a bunch of that in the world.

00:25:45.120 --> 00:25:48.660
And so to do an architecture like this, and this is

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:50.980
going to be different for every application, this is a very

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:51.730
serious thing.

00:25:51.750 --> 00:25:55.010
You need to be thinking hard about service boundaries, data boundaries

00:25:55.010 --> 00:25:57.260
, et cetera, even temporal coupling.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:02.300
The end sort of goal here, and really something that's

00:26:02.300 --> 00:26:05.760
always been true, is if we're on a team together

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:08.300
, what we are building is not the code.

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:09.620
We're building a system.

00:26:09.620 --> 00:26:12.350
And the code is not only not the asset, it is

00:26:12.350 --> 00:26:13.420
a liability.

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:14.490
It always is.

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:17.990
Because every line of code you ever wrote is legacy code the

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.500
moment you wrote it.

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:20.140
Right?

00:26:20.140 --> 00:26:21.500
Legacy code is bad.

00:26:21.500 --> 00:26:22.850
We all know that, right?

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:24.450
So the system is the asset.

00:26:24.460 --> 00:26:25.980
The code is a liability.

00:26:25.980 --> 00:26:29.780
So if you think about all this stuff I was just saying

00:26:29.780 --> 00:26:33.990
, you think about anything in your current systems, like pick

00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:35.500
one component.

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:36.840
Could you replace it tomorrow?

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:38.690
Could you just have Claude redo it?

00:26:38.690 --> 00:26:42.280
If not, you probably have a refactoring job,

00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:45.170
a system-wide refactoring job ahead of you.

00:26:45.170 --> 00:26:47.930
And I will assert you already have that refactoring job

00:26:47.980 --> 00:26:48.590
ahead of you.

00:26:48.590 --> 00:26:50.730
You just didn't know it yet because things are moving a

00:26:50.730 --> 00:26:52.630
thousand times faster than they used to.

00:26:52.630 --> 00:26:53.730
Or maybe faster than that.

00:26:53.740 --> 00:26:55.400
I don't know what the right number it is.

00:26:55.430 --> 00:27:00.330
So the point is AI didn't actually create this problem.

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:02.170
And I think that's true of a lot of stuff we

00:27:02.170 --> 00:27:04.560
're seeing now, both in terms of the problems we see

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:05.980
from AI and the solutions.

00:27:05.980 --> 00:27:08.570
It's like a real pattern I'm seeing.

00:27:08.620 --> 00:27:09.620
I'm also a VC.

00:27:09.620 --> 00:27:10.350
Sorry.

00:27:10.350 --> 00:27:13.320
I heard some shade to VCs on the last talk.

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:15.580
And I agree with it, honestly.

00:27:15.580 --> 00:27:17.200
I'm a VC who is also a programmer.

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:18.430
I talk to a lot of people.

00:27:18.430 --> 00:27:21.180
And a lot of things happening now that I think are really

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:24.160
powerful are like, AI is creating a problem because things move

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:26.850
so fast, so much content is getting created, et cetera

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:27.550
, et cetera.

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:29.660
So we're going to use AI to fix the problem.

00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:31.410
And that's kind of where I am right now.

00:27:31.510 --> 00:27:33.280
But it's the same thing we always had.

00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:35.870
It's just going a thousand miles per hour.

00:27:35.870 --> 00:27:39.250
So all this stuff I was talking about, how do we

00:27:39.250 --> 00:27:41.180
make it more concrete?

00:27:41.180 --> 00:27:45.650
Well, I told you I have a reference implementation of the

00:27:45.650 --> 00:27:47.030
Phoenix architecture.

00:27:47.030 --> 00:27:48.210
I linked it earlier.

00:27:48.210 --> 00:27:50.550
But I also told you the conversation is the commit.

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:52.960
And the things I was saying, I hope they were registering

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:55.100
like, well, I can't use Slack as my system

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:57.420
of record, or I can't use Teams or whatever,

00:27:57.420 --> 00:27:58.860
or Discord, right?

00:27:58.860 --> 00:28:01.830
I need something with, like, durability that I can host

00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:04.210
myself, that I can trust that no one else can read

00:28:04.210 --> 00:28:05.750
unless I want them to.

00:28:05.750 --> 00:28:08.220
I want cryptographic identities.

00:28:08.220 --> 00:28:10.280
I want provenance that way.

00:28:10.310 --> 00:28:12.470
I want my agents to be spawned by me and my

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:12.850
key.

00:28:12.870 --> 00:28:14.530
And I want them to have keys.

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:17.990
And I want us to maybe even have reputation and durability.

00:28:18.060 --> 00:28:21.540
And so I decided I would just build something that does this

00:28:21.540 --> 00:28:21.820
.

00:28:21.820 --> 00:28:23.180
It started as a hack one day.

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:25.420
And here's where it's an app protocol thing.

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:28.900
I was like, what if we could sign into IRC

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:31.250
, if you know what that is, internet relay chat for

00:28:31.380 --> 00:28:32.360
the young people?

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:35.020
What if we could sign up with your blue sky handle?

00:28:35.020 --> 00:28:37.980
And it just kind of got out of control.

00:28:37.980 --> 00:28:42.670
So now what I'm building is a substrate with all of

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:46.180
these properties, agent provenance, etc., etc.

00:28:46.180 --> 00:28:47.420
There's a lot to it.

00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:53.470
But the end goal is the substrate for agent-driven development

00:28:53.780 --> 00:28:55.060
with Phoenix.

00:28:55.100 --> 00:28:57.860
And so please join freak.

00:28:57.860 --> 00:28:58.530
at.

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:00.380
Please contribute stuff.

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:02.470
Tell me what's stupid, what's not great.

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:05.670
It kind of looks like there's iOS, Android, Windows

00:29:05.670 --> 00:29:09.420
, Web, TUI, Rust SDK, bot SDK,

00:29:09.420 --> 00:29:10.340
great docs.

00:29:10.350 --> 00:29:11.820
It's ready for you.

00:29:11.820 --> 00:29:13.740
But I have not launched it.

00:29:13.740 --> 00:29:16.140
And don't tell anyone about it.

00:29:16.140 --> 00:29:18.790
But please join because it's just for nerds right now

00:29:18.790 --> 00:29:18.960
.

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.940
But I think this is how things are going to work in

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:21.740
the future.

00:29:21.740 --> 00:29:23.320
And I guess I'm out of time.

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:25.870
So thank you very much for your attention.

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:31.500
Thank you very much, Chad.

00:29:31.500 --> 00:29:37.580
Accidentally an encrypted IRC client with app portal accounts.

00:29:37.580 --> 00:29:38.140
Amazing.

00:29:38.140 --> 00:29:40.700
Thank you very much.
